Note:
LUA SEMANTIC ANALYZER - resolves names and captures over the Lua AST

The Lua parser (lua_parser.runa) produces a tree of LuaASTNode records whose
node_type field is one of the LUA_* constants and whose positional children
carry the sub-structure (see the per-node child contract documented inline at
each analyze_* Process). This pass runs over that real AST - it does NOT invent
a parallel node schema - and enforces the SEMANTIC rules Lua's grammar alone
does not express:

  1. Lexical name resolution. Every identifier reference is resolved against a
     scope chain of name->declaration-level symbol tables. A name found in the
     innermost scope is a local; a name found in an enclosing scope that lies
     across a function boundary is an UPVALUE (captured by the closure); a name
     found nowhere is a GLOBAL (Lua resolves unknown names through the global
     environment table _G at run time, and an assignment to an unknown name
     implicitly creates a global).

  2. Closure upvalue capture. Lua closures capture variables from enclosing
     function scopes. When analyze_lua_variable resolves a reference to a
     binding declared at a function-scope level shallower than the innermost
     enclosing function, it records the name in the analyzer's upvalue set via
     mark_as_upvalue; analyze_upvalues then reconciles every recorded capture
     against the function scope that introduced it so closure lowering can
     materialise the capture slots.

  3. Standard-library surface. Lua programs reference print, type, pairs,
     string.format, math.pi, table.insert, io.write, etc. without declaring
     them. setup_global_environment pre-populates the global environment with
     the canonical Lua 5.4 library surface so an undefined-global diagnostic
     fires only for genuinely unknown names, not for stdlib references.

  4. Structural / usage validation. validate_lua_* walks the recorded analysis
     state to surface genuine problems: references that resolved to nothing and
     are not stdlib (undefined), goto targets with no matching label, break
     outside any loop, and unbalanced assignment target/value lists.

The symbol tables are STRING-KEYED dictionaries (dictionary.runa over the
content-hashing hashtable): keys are the identifier strings the parser copied
into LuaASTNode.value, values are the 1-based declaration level (level+1, so 0
unambiguously means "absent"). A string key keyed by content - not an
integer-keyed table indexed by a string pointer - is mandatory; the latter
hashes pointer identity and corrupts on the parser's distinct heap copies.

Dependencies:
- lua_parser.runa            (LuaASTNode shape, LUA_* node constants, accessors)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/lua/lua_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Analyzer State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The analyzer threads its resolution state through the recursive walk in a
single heap record. Two scope handles model the lexical chain: current_scope is
the innermost (most recently entered) name->level table, and scope_stack holds
every enclosing scope with the global environment at the bottom, so a lookup
walks current_scope then the stack from top down to global. Parallel to
scope_stack, scope_is_function records whether each stacked scope is a function
boundary, and the matching current_is_function flag classifies the innermost
scope; these let the analyzer decide local-vs-upvalue when a name resolves in an
enclosing scope. current_level is the lexical depth of the innermost scope (0 at
global). global_env is the persistent stdlib + implicit-global table and never
leaves the bottom of the chain. upvalues, errors, and warnings are append/keyed
accumulators surfaced to the caller; loop_depth gates break/continue validity;
labels collects every label seen and goto_targets every goto so the final pass
can match them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sixteen 8-byte slots at fixed offsets 0..120 referenced directly by the
accessors below: global_env(0), current_scope(8), scope_stack(16),
scope_is_function(24), current_is_function(32), current_level(40), upvalues(48),
errors(56), warnings(64), has_error(72), loop_depth(80), labels(88),
goto_targets(96), goto_lines(104), break_lines(112), unbalanced_lines(120).
Total 128 bytes. The four trailing line lists pair positionally with their
target lists so a diagnostic can name the offending source line.
@End Implementation

Type called "LuaSemanticAnalyzer":
    global_env as Integer           Note: Dict string-key -> 1 (stdlib + implicit globals)
    current_scope as Integer        Note: Dict string-key -> level+1 (innermost scope)
    scope_stack as Integer          Note: List of enclosing scope Dicts (global at bottom)
    scope_is_function as Integer     Note: List parallel to scope_stack: 1 if that scope is a function boundary
    current_is_function as Integer   Note: Boolean: 1 if innermost scope is a function boundary
    current_level as Integer        Note: Lexical depth of innermost scope (0 = global)
    upvalues as Integer             Note: Dict string-key -> 1 (names captured as upvalues)
    errors as Integer               Note: List of error message strings
    warnings as Integer             Note: List of warning message strings
    has_error as Integer            Note: Boolean: 1 if any error recorded
    loop_depth as Integer           Note: Number of enclosing loops (break legality)
    labels as Integer               Note: Dict string-key -> 1 (labels declared)
    goto_targets as Integer         Note: List of goto target label strings
    goto_lines as Integer           Note: List of goto source lines (parallel to goto_targets)
    break_lines as Integer          Note: List of break source lines outside any loop
    unbalanced_lines as Integer      Note: List of assignment source lines flagged for inspection
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Analyzer Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The constructor allocates every sub-collection eagerly so the recursive walk
never has to null-check a table or list handle. The global environment doubles
as the bottom scope: current_scope starts AS global_env and current_level is 0,
so top-level statements resolve and declare against the global table without a
special case. setup_global_environment seeds the Lua 5.4 standard-library names
into global_env before any analysis runs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 128 bytes; return 0 on OOM. Create global_env, scope_stack,
scope_is_function, upvalues, errors, warnings, labels, goto_targets, goto_lines,
break_lines, and unbalanced_lines. Install global_env at offsets 0 and 8 (it is
both the global table and the initial current scope), zero current_is_function /
current_level / has_error / loop_depth, and store the collection handles at
their offsets. Seed the stdlib, then return the analyzer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_lua_semantic_analyzer" takes nothing returns Integer:
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with 128

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let global_env be proc create from Dict
    Let scope_stack be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let scope_is_function be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let upvalues be proc create from Dict
    Let errors be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let warnings be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let labels be proc create from Dict
    Let goto_targets be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let goto_lines be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let break_lines be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let unbalanced_lines be proc list_create from ListCore

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, global_env
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, global_env
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, scope_stack
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, scope_is_function
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, upvalues
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, errors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88, labels
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96, goto_targets
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104, goto_lines
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112, break_lines
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120, unbalanced_lines

    proc setup_global_environment with analyzer

    Return analyzer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Diagnostics
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Errors and warnings are accumulated in append-only lists so a single analysis
pass surfaces every problem rather than aborting on the first. record_error also
latches has_error to 1 so a caller can gate lowering on one boolean without
scanning the list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Append message to the errors list (offset 56) and set has_error (offset 72) to 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "record_error" takes analyzer as Integer, message as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    proc list_append from ListCore with errors, message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Warnings track non-fatal observations (undefined-global heuristics, shadowing)
that do not block lowering; they are kept separate from errors so a caller can
report them without failing the analysis.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Append message to the warnings list (offset 64). has_error is left untouched.
@End Implementation

Process called "record_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, message as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64
    proc list_append from ListCore with warnings, message
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Scope Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Entering a scope pushes the current scope (and its function-boundary flag) onto
the stacks, installs a fresh empty name table as the innermost scope, raises the
level, and records whether the new scope is itself a function boundary. Block
scopes (do/while/for bodies) pass is_function=0 so they do not interrupt the
upvalue chain; function and function-expression bodies pass is_function=1 so a
name resolved beyond that boundary is classified as a capture.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Push current_scope onto scope_stack (offset 16) and current_is_function onto
scope_is_function (offset 24). Allocate a fresh Dict and store it at offset 8.
Store is_function at offset 32, and current_level+1 at offset 40.
@End Implementation

Process called "enter_scope" takes analyzer as Integer, is_function as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let func_flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    Let cur_is_func be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    Let level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40

    proc list_append from ListCore with stack, current
    proc list_append from ListCore with func_flags, cur_is_func

    Let fresh be proc create from Dict
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, fresh
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, is_function
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, level plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exiting restores the scope and function-boundary flag saved by the matching
enter_scope and lowers the level. The global scope is never popped: it is the
permanent bottom of the chain installed at construction, and analyze never calls
exit_scope more times than enter_scope, so the stack cannot underflow during a
well-formed walk - the depth guard makes the underflow path a no-op rather than
a crash if a malformed AST drives it there.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If scope_stack is empty, return without change. Pop the saved scope from
scope_stack (offset 16) into current_scope (offset 8); pop the saved flag from
scope_is_function (offset 24) into current_is_function (offset 32); lower
current_level (offset 40) by 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "exit_scope" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let depth be proc list_length from ListCore with stack

    If depth is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let func_flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    Let level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40

    Let restored_scope be proc list_pop from ListCore with stack
    Let restored_flag be proc list_pop from ListCore with func_flags

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, restored_scope
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, restored_flag
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, level minus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Declares a name in the innermost scope at the current lexical level, encoding the
level as level+1 so a lookup can distinguish "declared at level 0" from "absent"
(both of which would otherwise read back as 0 from the value-0-means-missing
dictionary). Re-declaration in the same scope simply overwrites - Lua permits
re-declaring a local, with the later binding shadowing the earlier one.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read current_scope (offset 8) and current_level (offset 40); set name -> level+1
in that scope.
@End Implementation

Process called "declare_local" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Nothing:
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let scope be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    proc set from Dict with scope, name, level plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Resolves a name to its declaration level by walking the scope chain innermost
first: current_scope, then each stacked scope from the most recently pushed
downward, ending at the global table. Returns the stored level+1 encoding (so a
non-zero result is "found at level result-1") or 0 if the name is bound nowhere
in any lexical scope. The global table is included by walking the full stack
down to its bottom entry, which IS the global environment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Check current_scope (offset 8) via Dict.get; if non-zero return it. Otherwise
walk scope_stack (offset 16) from index size-1 down to 0, returning the first
non-zero Dict.get. Return 0 if no scope binds the name.
@End Implementation

Process called "resolve_name_level" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let found be proc get from Dict with current, name
    If found is not equal to 0:
        Return found
    End If

    Let stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let depth be proc list_length from ListCore with stack
    Let i be depth minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let scope be proc list_get from ListCore with stack, i
        Let hit be proc get from Dict with scope, name
        If hit is not equal to 0:
            Return hit
        End If
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Standard Library Surface
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lua programs reference the standard library without declaring it. Seeding the
canonical Lua 5.4 surface into the global environment lets the undefined-global
heuristic fire only on genuinely unknown names. Both the bare global functions
(print, type, pairs, ...) and the dotted module accessors actually written in
source (string.format, math.pi, table.insert, ...) are registered; the module
tables themselves (string, table, math, io, os, coroutine, package, debug) are
registered as globals so a reference to the bare module name also resolves.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read global_env (offset 0) once and register each name with value 1. Names are
grouped by module for readability but all land in the single flat global table,
which is also the bottom scope of the resolution chain.
@End Implementation

Process called "setup_global_environment" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0

    Note: Global functions and values
    proc set from Dict with env, "assert", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "collectgarbage", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "dofile", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "error", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "getmetatable", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "setmetatable", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "ipairs", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "pairs", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "next", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "load", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "loadfile", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "pcall", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "xpcall", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "print", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "rawequal", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "rawget", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "rawset", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "rawlen", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "require", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "select", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "tonumber", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "tostring", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "type", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "_G", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "_VERSION", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "_ENV", 1

    Note: Standard module tables (bare module-name references)
    proc set from Dict with env, "string", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "table", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "math", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "io", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "os", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "coroutine", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "package", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "debug", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "utf8", 1

    Note: string.*
    proc set from Dict with env, "string.byte", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "string.char", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "string.dump", 1
    proc set from Dict with env, "string.find", 1
