@Reasoning:
Basic-type metatable bookkeeping in Lua attaches the per-type metatables Lua
installs for strings (the string library is the string metatable's __index).
Recording the string-metatable binding in the global environment ensures a
method-call on a string literal (("x"):upper()) resolves rather than tripping
the undefined-global heuristic. This is the real Lua behaviour: only the string
type carries a default metatable, exposed through the string library table.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read global_env (offset 0) and register the string type's metatable binding so
string method dispatch resolves. The other base types (number, boolean, nil,
function) have no default metatable in stock Lua, so none is registered.
@End Implementation

Process called "setup_basic_metatables" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    proc set from Dict with env, "string", 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lua creates a global implicitly when an unknown name is assigned to. This records
the name in the global environment so subsequent references resolve, and is
called from assignment analysis when an assignment target resolves to no local.
The name is the live key the parser copied from source; storing it with value 1
matches the stdlib seeding convention.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read global_env (offset 0); set name -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_implicit_global" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Nothing:
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    proc set from Dict with env, name, 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Upvalue Capture
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A name resolved to a binding declared in an enclosing function scope - i.e. at a
lexical level shallower than the innermost enclosing function - is captured by
the current closure as an upvalue. mark_as_upvalue records the captured name in
the analyzer's upvalue set so closure lowering can materialise a capture slot;
recording by name (not level) is sufficient because Lua upvalues are identified
by the captured variable's name within the closure.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read upvalues (offset 48) and set name -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "mark_as_upvalue" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Nothing:
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let upvalues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    proc set from Dict with upvalues, name, 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Determines whether a name resolved at decl_level is captured across a function
boundary relative to the innermost scope. The innermost enclosing function
boundary sits at some level >= the level of the nearest is_function scope; any
binding declared at a strictly shallower level than that boundary, when the
current scope is inside a function, is an upvalue. The check is conservative and
exact for the common closure forms: if the resolved declaration level is less
than the current function-boundary level, the name crosses the boundary.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compute the level of the nearest enclosing function boundary by scanning
scope_is_function (offset 24) from the top down for the first set flag, mapping
its stack index to a level; if the innermost scope is itself a function the
boundary is current_level. If decl_level (the resolve result minus 1) is less
than that boundary level, the name is captured: return 1, else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_upvalue_capture" takes analyzer as Integer, decl_level as Integer returns Integer:
    Let current_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let cur_is_func be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32

    Note: Find the lexical level of the nearest enclosing function boundary.
    Let boundary_level be 0
    Let found_boundary be 0

    If cur_is_func is equal to 1:
        Set boundary_level to current_level
        Set found_boundary to 1
    End If

    If found_boundary is equal to 0:
        Let func_flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
        Let depth be proc list_length from ListCore with func_flags
        Let i be depth minus 1
        While i is greater than or equal to 0:
            Let flag be proc list_get from ListCore with func_flags, i
            If flag is equal to 1:
                Note: Stack index i corresponds to lexical level i+1
                Set boundary_level to i plus 1
                Set found_boundary to 1
                Set i to 0 minus 1
            Otherwise:
                Set i to i minus 1
            End If
        End While
    End If

    If found_boundary is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If decl_level is less than boundary_level:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Post-function-body reconciliation hook. By the time a function body has been
walked, every cross-boundary reference has already been recorded into the
analyzer's upvalue set by analyze_lua_variable via mark_as_upvalue. This pass
finalises that set against the just-closed function scope: it confirms the
captured names are no longer in scope (the enclosing binding was popped) and
leaves the analyzer's upvalue set as the authoritative capture record for
lowering. Because the set is name-keyed and shared across the walk, no
per-function copy is needed - the caller reads it after analyze returns.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the upvalues set (offset 48). For every captured name still resolvable in
the (now enclosing) scope chain at a shallower level, the capture is confirmed;
names that no longer resolve anywhere are left recorded (Lua permits capturing a
local that has since gone out of textual scope). The set is the result, so this
pass performs the confirmation walk and returns having validated the invariant
that the upvalue set is non-empty exactly when at least one capture occurred.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_upvalues" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let upvalues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let captured_keys be proc keys from Dict with upvalues
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with captured_keys

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let name be proc list_get from ListCore with captured_keys, i
        Let level be proc resolve_name_level with analyzer, name
        If level is not equal to 0:
            Note: The captured binding remains visible in an enclosing scope;
            Note: re-affirm its membership in the capture set so a later
            Note: re-entry of the same scope keeps the binding marked.
            proc set from Dict with upvalues, name, 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST Traversal Dispatch
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Recursive node-kind dispatcher over the real LuaASTNode tree. Each LUA_*
constant routes to the analyzer that understands that node's child contract.
A null node is a no-op (a missing optional child such as an absent for-step or
empty return is represented by a missing child, which callers guard before
recursing). Unknown kinds fall through to analyze_generic so forward-compatible
HIR extensions traverse their children without crashing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Bind node_ptr as Parser.LuaASTNode, branch on node.node_type against the
Parser.LUA_* constants, and delegate. Returns Nothing; all state lives on the
analyzer.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_node" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    If node_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node_ptr
    Let kind be node.node_type

    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_PROGRAM:
        proc analyze_lua_program with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_BLOCK:
        proc analyze_lua_block with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_FUNCTION:
        proc analyze_lua_function with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_LOCAL_DECLARATION:
        proc analyze_lua_local_declaration with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_ASSIGNMENT:
        proc analyze_lua_assignment with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_IF_STATEMENT:
        proc analyze_lua_if_statement with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_WHILE_STATEMENT:
        proc analyze_lua_while_statement with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_REPEAT_STATEMENT:
        proc analyze_lua_repeat_statement with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_FOR_NUMERIC:
        proc analyze_lua_for_numeric with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_FOR_GENERIC:
        proc analyze_lua_for_generic with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_FUNCTION_CALL:
        proc analyze_lua_function_call with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_RETURN_STATEMENT:
        proc analyze_lua_return_statement with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_BREAK_STATEMENT:
        proc analyze_lua_break_statement with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_LABEL_STATEMENT:
        proc analyze_lua_label_statement with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_GOTO_STATEMENT:
        proc analyze_lua_goto_statement with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_BINARY_OP:
        proc analyze_lua_binary_op with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_UNARY_OP:
        proc analyze_lua_unary_op with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_IDENTIFIER:
        proc analyze_lua_variable with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_NUMBER_LITERAL:
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_STRING_LITERAL:
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_BOOLEAN_LITERAL:
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_NIL_LITERAL:
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_TABLE_CONSTRUCTOR:
        proc analyze_lua_table_constructor with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_FUNCTION_EXPRESSION:
        proc analyze_lua_function_expression with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_VARARG:
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_INDEX_ACCESS:
        proc analyze_lua_index_access with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.LUA_FIELD_ACCESS:
        proc analyze_lua_field_access with analyzer, node_ptr
        Return
    End If

    proc analyze_generic_lua_node with analyzer, node_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
A program node wraps a single block child. Lua treats the top-level chunk as the
body of an implicit vararg function (the "main chunk"), so the chunk runs in its
OWN function scope rather than directly in the global environment: a chunk-level
"local x" is a local of the main chunk, distinct from a true global created by a
bare assignment. Entering a function scope for the chunk body is therefore
correct - it keeps chunk-level locals out of the global table and makes a
chunk-level "local function f" resolve as a local, not a global, while a bare
"x = 1" still falls through to the global environment via the resolution chain.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Enter a function scope (the implicit main-chunk function), walk child 0 (the
block), reconcile any upvalues the chunk captured (the chunk has no enclosing
function scope, so this confirms an empty capture set and keeps the per-function
discipline uniform), then exit the scope.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_program" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let block be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    proc enter_scope with analyzer, 1
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, block
    proc analyze_upvalues with analyzer
    proc exit_scope with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
A block is a flat statement list. A block does NOT introduce its own scope in
this analyzer: the scope-introducing constructs (function, function expression,
for loops, while/repeat bodies are entered by their own analyzers) push the
scope and then walk the block as their body, so the block analyzer simply
iterates its statement children. Walking statements left to right preserves
declaration-before-use ordering for local resolution.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read child count; analyze each child statement in order.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_block" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node_ptr
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, i
        proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A named function declaration (children: name, params, body). The function's name
is declared in the CURRENT scope (so the function can be referenced after - and,
for a Lua global function, becomes a global binding); then a fresh function scope
is entered, parameters are declared as locals in it, the body is walked, upvalues
are reconciled, and the scope is exited. The name child may be a dotted/method
field-access (function t.f() / function t:m()), in which case the base of the
access is the binding that must already exist - we analyze it as a reference
rather than declaring it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Child 0 is the name node, child 1 the LUA_PARAMETER_LIST, child 2 the body block.
If the name is a plain identifier, declare it in the current scope; otherwise
analyze it as a reference (field/index access resolves its base). Enter a
function scope, declare every parameter identifier (LUA_VARARG params are
skipped - "..." is not a name), walk the body, reconcile upvalues, exit.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_function" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let name_node be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    Let params be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 1
    Let body be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 2

    If name_node is not equal to 0:
        Let name as Parser.LuaASTNode be name_node
        If name.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_IDENTIFIER:
            proc declare_local with analyzer, name.value
        Otherwise:
            proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, name_node
        End If
    End If

    proc enter_scope with analyzer, 1
    proc declare_parameters with analyzer, params
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, body
    proc analyze_upvalues with analyzer
    proc exit_scope with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
An anonymous function expression (children: params, body). Identical capture
semantics to a named function but with no name to declare in the enclosing scope.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Child 0 is the LUA_PARAMETER_LIST, child 1 the body block. Enter a function
scope, declare parameters, walk the body, reconcile upvalues, exit.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_function_expression" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let params be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    Let body be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 1

    proc enter_scope with analyzer, 1
    proc declare_parameters with analyzer, params
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, body
    proc analyze_upvalues with analyzer
    proc exit_scope with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Declares each parameter of a LUA_PARAMETER_LIST as a local in the current
(function) scope. The vararg marker "..." (LUA_VARARG) is a parameter position
but not a nameable binding, so it is skipped - referencing it is handled as a
vararg expression, not a name lookup.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guard the list for null. For each child: if it is a LUA_IDENTIFIER, declare its
value; LUA_VARARG children are skipped.
@End Implementation

Process called "declare_parameters" takes analyzer as Integer, params_node as Integer returns Nothing:
    If params_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with params_node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let param be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with params_node, i
        Let p as Parser.LuaASTNode be param
        If p.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_IDENTIFIER:
            proc declare_local with analyzer, p.value
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
"local a, b = e1, e2" (children: name_list, optional expr_list). Lua evaluates
the initializer expressions in the ENCLOSING scope before the new locals come
into being, so the expression list is analyzed first (resolving against scopes
that do NOT yet contain the new names), and only then are the names declared.
This is the rule that makes "local x = x" capture the outer x on the right and
introduce a fresh local x on the left. The local-function form (single
LUA_FUNCTION child) declares the name BEFORE walking the body so the function can
recurse on itself.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read child 0. If it is a LUA_FUNCTION (local function form), declare the function
name in the current scope first, then analyze the function node (which enters its
own scope) so recursion resolves. Otherwise child 0 is the LUA_NAME_LIST and an
optional child 1 is the LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST: analyze every initializer
expression first, then declare every name in the name list.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_local_declaration" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node_ptr
    Let first be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0

    If first is not equal to 0:
        Let f as Parser.LuaASTNode be first
        If f.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_FUNCTION:
            Note: local function form: declare the bound name, then walk the body.
            Let inner_name be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with first, 0
            If inner_name is not equal to 0:
                Let n as Parser.LuaASTNode be inner_name
                proc declare_local with analyzer, n.value
            End If
            proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, first
            Return
        End If
    End If

    Note: variable form: analyze initializers (child 1) before declaring names.
    If count is greater than 1:
        Let expr_list be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 1
        proc analyze_expression_list with analyzer, expr_list
    End If

    proc declare_name_list with analyzer, first
End Process

@Reasoning:
Declares every LUA_IDENTIFIER in a LUA_NAME_LIST as a local in the current scope.
Shared by local declarations and for-in loop-variable binding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guard the list for null; for each child that is a LUA_IDENTIFIER, declare its
value.
@End Implementation

Process called "declare_name_list" takes analyzer as Integer, name_list as Integer returns Nothing:
    If name_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with name_list
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let name be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with name_list, i
        Let n as Parser.LuaASTNode be name
        If n.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_IDENTIFIER:
            proc declare_local with analyzer, n.value
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Analyzes every expression in a LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST / LUA_ARGUMENT_LIST by
dispatching each child through analyze_lua_node. Used for initializer lists,
assignment value lists, return lists, and call arguments.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guard for null; analyze each child in order.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_expression_list" takes analyzer as Integer, list_node as Integer returns Nothing:
    If list_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with list_node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let expr be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with list_node, i
        proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, expr
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
"t1, t2 = e1, e2" (children: lhs_list, rhs_list). Values are evaluated before
assignment, so the RHS list is analyzed first. Each LHS target is then resolved:
a bare identifier that resolves to no local and is not already a global is an
implicit global creation (the defining Lua behaviour for "x = 1" at top level);
a field/index target is analyzed as an expression (its base must resolve). When
the target and value counts differ, the source line is recorded for the
balance check so a caller can flag the mismatch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Child 0 is the LHS LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST, child 1 the RHS list. Analyze the RHS
list first. For each LHS target: if it is a plain identifier, resolve it; an
unresolved, non-global identifier becomes an implicit global. Other target forms
(field/index) are analyzed as expressions. Record the node line in
unbalanced_lines when LHS and RHS counts differ.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_assignment" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let lhs be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    Let rhs be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 1

    proc analyze_expression_list with analyzer, rhs

    If lhs is not equal to 0:
        Let lcount be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with lhs
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than lcount:
            Let target be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with lhs, i
            Let t as Parser.LuaASTNode be target
            If t.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_IDENTIFIER:
                Let level be proc resolve_name_level with analyzer, t.value
                If level is equal to 0:
                    Let env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
                    Let is_global be proc contains from Dict with env, t.value
                    If is_global is equal to 0:
                        proc create_implicit_global with analyzer, t.value
                    End If
                End If
            Otherwise:
                proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, target
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Note: Record target/value count imbalance for the validation pass.
        If rhs is not equal to 0:
            Let rcount be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with rhs
            If lcount is not equal to rcount:
                Let node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node_ptr
                Let lines be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120
                proc list_append from ListCore with lines, node.line
            End If
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
"if c1 then b1 elseif c2 then b2 ... else bn end" (children: c1, b1, [c2, b2,
...], [else_block]). Conditions and blocks alternate, with a trailing
condition-less else block when the child count is odd. Each block is a fresh
lexical scope (Lua's if/elseif/else arms scope their locals), entered as a
non-function block scope so locals do not leak between arms but upvalue chains
are preserved.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk children pairwise: at even index i analyze child i as a condition; child
i+1, if present, is a block analyzed inside a fresh block scope. A final lone
child (odd total count) is the else block, analyzed inside its own block scope.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_if_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node_ptr
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let remaining be count minus i
        If remaining is equal to 1:
            Note: trailing else block (no condition)
            Let else_block be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, i
            proc enter_scope with analyzer, 0
            proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, else_block
            proc exit_scope with analyzer
            Set i to i plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Let cond be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, i
            Let block be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, i plus 1
            proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, cond
            proc enter_scope with analyzer, 0
            proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, block
            proc exit_scope with analyzer
            Set i to i plus 2
        End If
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
"while c do b end" (children: condition, body). The condition is evaluated in the
enclosing scope; the body is a fresh block scope and is a loop, so loop_depth is
raised across the body to legalise break.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Analyze child 0 (condition). Raise loop_depth, enter a block scope, analyze child
1 (body), exit, lower loop_depth.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_while_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let cond be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    Let body be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 1

    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, cond

    proc enter_loop with analyzer
    proc enter_scope with analyzer, 0
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, body
    proc exit_scope with analyzer
    proc exit_loop with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
"repeat b until c" (children: body, condition). Lua's repeat is unique: the until
condition is evaluated in the SCOPE OF THE BODY, so locals declared in the body
are visible to the condition. The body scope is therefore kept open while the
condition is analyzed, then closed. The body is a loop, so loop_depth is raised.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Raise loop_depth, enter a block scope, analyze child 0 (body), THEN analyze child
1 (condition) while the body scope is still current, exit the scope, lower
loop_depth.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_repeat_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let body be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    Let cond be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 1

    proc enter_loop with analyzer
    proc enter_scope with analyzer, 0
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, body
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, cond
    proc exit_scope with analyzer
    proc exit_loop with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
"for v = start, stop[, step] do b end" (children: loop_var, start, stop, [step],
... body is the last child). The numeric range expressions are evaluated in the
enclosing scope, then a fresh loop scope is entered binding the single control
variable, and the body is walked. The parser appends the body as the final child
after the 2 or 3 range expressions, so the body index is child_count-1 and the
range expressions are children 1..body_index-1.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Child 0 is the loop-variable identifier. The last child is the body block; the
children between index 1 and body_index-1 are the start/stop/(step) expressions,
analyzed in the enclosing scope. Raise loop_depth, enter a block scope, declare
the loop variable, walk the body, exit, lower loop_depth.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_for_numeric" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node_ptr
    Let loop_var be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    Let body_index be count minus 1

    Note: Range expressions occupy children 1 .. body_index-1, evaluated outside the loop scope.
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than body_index:
        Let range_expr be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, i
        proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, range_expr
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc enter_loop with analyzer
    proc enter_scope with analyzer, 0

    If loop_var is not equal to 0:
        Let lv as Parser.LuaASTNode be loop_var
        proc declare_local with analyzer, lv.value
    End If

    Let body be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, body_index
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, body

    proc exit_scope with analyzer
    proc exit_loop with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
"for k, v in iter do b end" (children: name_list, expr_list, body). The iterator
expression list is evaluated in the enclosing scope (it is the generic-for
iterator triplet), then a fresh loop scope binds the loop variables and the body
is walked. Iterators evaluated before the loop variables exist is mandatory:
"for k in pairs(t)" must resolve pairs and t outside the loop scope.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Child 0 is the LUA_NAME_LIST, child 1 the LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST of iterators, child
2 the body. Analyze the iterator list in the enclosing scope; raise loop_depth,
enter a block scope, declare the name list, walk the body, exit, lower loop_depth.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_for_generic" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let name_list be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    Let expr_list be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 1
    Let body be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 2

    proc analyze_expression_list with analyzer, expr_list

    proc enter_loop with analyzer
    proc enter_scope with analyzer, 0
    proc declare_name_list with analyzer, name_list
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, body
    proc exit_scope with analyzer
    proc exit_loop with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
"f(args)" (children: function_expr, arg_list). The callee expression is analyzed
(resolving the function name / field access), then every argument. Both are
ordinary expression positions; no scope is introduced.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Analyze child 0 (the callee expression) and child 1 (the LUA_ARGUMENT_LIST).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_function_call" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let callee be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    Let args be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 1

    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, callee
    proc analyze_expression_list with analyzer, args
End Process

@Reasoning:
"return e1, e2, ..." (children: optional expr_list). A bare "return" has no
children. The return expression list is analyzed in the current scope; return
introduces no binding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the node has a child, analyze child 0 as the LUA_EXPRESSION_LIST; otherwise no-op.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_return_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node_ptr
    If count is greater than 0:
        Let expr_list be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
        proc analyze_expression_list with analyzer, expr_list
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
"break" (no children). break is legal only inside a loop; outside any loop it is
a semantic error. The source line is recorded so the validation pass can emit a
precise diagnostic, mirroring how Lua rejects a break with no enclosing loop.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read loop_depth (offset 80). If 0, append the node line to break_lines (offset
112). Otherwise no-op.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_break_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let loop_depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    If loop_depth is equal to 0:
        Let node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node_ptr
        Let break_lines be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
        proc list_append from ListCore with break_lines, node.line
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
"::label::" (no children; name in value). Records the label name in the labels
set so a forward or backward goto can be matched against it by the validation
pass. Lua labels are unique within a block but this analyzer's set-membership
check is sufficient for the undefined-label diagnostic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read node.value (the label name) and the labels set (offset 88); set name -> 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_label_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node_ptr
    If node.value is not equal to 0:
        Let labels be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
        proc set from Dict with labels, node.value, 1
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
"goto label" (no children; target name in value). Records the target name and the
goto's source line so the validation pass can confirm a matching label exists.
Because a goto may target a label that appears LATER in the source, the match is
deferred to the final pass after the whole chunk has been walked and every label
recorded.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read node.value (the target name); append it to goto_targets (offset 96) and the
node line to goto_lines (offset 104), keeping the two lists positionally paired.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_goto_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node_ptr
    If node.value is not equal to 0:
        Let targets be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
        Let lines be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
        proc list_append from ListCore with targets, node.value
        proc list_append from ListCore with lines, node.line
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
A binary operation (children: left, right; value: operator). Both operands are
analyzed as expressions; the operator itself needs no resolution.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Analyze child 0 (left) and child 1 (right).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_binary_op" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let left be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    Let right be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 1
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, left
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, right
End Process

@Reasoning:
A unary operation (children: operand; value: operator). The operand is analyzed
as an expression.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Analyze child 0 (operand).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_unary_op" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let operand be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, operand
End Process

@Reasoning:
A table constructor (children: zero or more fields, each a LUA_TABLE_FIELD,
LUA_TABLE_FIELD_NAMED, or LUA_TABLE_FIELD_INDEXED). The fields are analyzed by
recursing into their value (and, for indexed fields, key) expressions; a named
field's name child is a literal key, not a variable reference, so it is not
resolved.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For each field child, dispatch by its node_type: positional field -> analyze its
single value child; named field -> analyze child 1 (value), skip child 0 (the
literal key name); indexed field -> analyze child 0 (key expr) and child 1
(value expr). Unknown field kinds analyze all their children defensively.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_table_constructor" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node_ptr
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let field be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, i
        Let f as Parser.LuaASTNode be field
        If f.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_TABLE_FIELD:
            Let v be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with field, 0
            proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, v
        Otherwise:
            If f.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_TABLE_FIELD_NAMED:
                Let nv be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with field, 1
                proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, nv
            Otherwise:
                If f.node_type is equal to Parser.LUA_TABLE_FIELD_INDEXED:
                    Let k be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with field, 0
                    Let iv be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with field, 1
                    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, k
                    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, iv
                Otherwise:
                    proc analyze_generic_lua_node with analyzer, field
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
"obj[expr]" (children: object, index_expr). Both the object expression and the
index expression are ordinary expression positions and are analyzed; the index
is a value, not a name, so it resolves through normal expression analysis.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Analyze child 0 (object) and child 1 (index expression).
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_index_access" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let object be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    Let index be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 1
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, object
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, index
End Process

@Reasoning:
"obj.field" (children: object, field_name). The object expression is analyzed
(its base name must resolve), but the field name child is a literal selector, not
a variable reference, so it is NOT resolved against the scope chain - resolving
it would spuriously flag every field access as an undefined global.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Analyze child 0 (the object expression) only; child 1 (the field-name identifier)
is a selector and is deliberately not resolved.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_field_access" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let object be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, 0
    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, object
End Process

@Reasoning:
A variable reference (LUA_IDENTIFIER used in expression position; name in value).
This is the core resolution rule. The name is looked up through the scope chain.
If it resolves to a binding declared at a level shallower than the innermost
enclosing function boundary, it is captured as an upvalue. If it resolves
nowhere AND is not a known global (stdlib or implicit), it is a probable
undefined-global reference, recorded as a warning rather than a hard error
because Lua resolves any unknown name through _G at run time and a single-file
frontend cannot see names injected by an embedding host.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read node.value. Resolve via resolve_name_level. If level is non-zero, decode the
declaration level (level-1) and, if is_upvalue_capture says it crosses a function
boundary, mark it captured. If level is zero, check the global environment; an
unknown name is recorded as an undefined-global warning and added to the global
table so repeated references do not multiply the warning.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_variable" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let node as Parser.LuaASTNode be node_ptr
    Let name be node.value

    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let level be proc resolve_name_level with analyzer, name
    If level is not equal to 0:
        Let decl_level be level minus 1
        Let captured be proc is_upvalue_capture with analyzer, decl_level
        If captured is equal to 1:
            proc mark_as_upvalue with analyzer, name
        End If
        Return
    End If

    Let env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let is_global be proc contains from Dict with env, name
    If is_global is equal to 0:
        proc record_warning with analyzer, "Reference to undefined global variable in Lua source"
        proc set from Dict with env, name, 1
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Forward-compatible fallback for any node kind without a dedicated analyzer: walk
its children so a future HIR/AST extension still has its sub-expressions resolved
rather than silently skipped. No scope is introduced.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read child count; analyze each child via analyze_lua_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_generic_lua_node" takes analyzer as Integer, node_ptr as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let count be proc ast_node_child_count from Parser with node_ptr
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc ast_node_get_child from Parser with node_ptr, i
        proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Loop-Depth Tracking
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Raising loop_depth on loop entry legalises break within the body; the matching
lowering on exit restores the enclosing legality. A counter (not a flag) is
required because nested loops must keep break legal until the outermost loop is
left.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read loop_depth (offset 80); store loop_depth+1.
@End Implementation

Process called "enter_loop" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, depth plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Restores loop_depth on loop exit. Guarded against underflow so a malformed AST
cannot drive the counter negative.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read loop_depth (offset 80); if greater than 0, store loop_depth-1.
@End Implementation

Process called "exit_loop" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let depth be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    If depth is greater than 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, depth minus 1
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Final Validation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The final validation pass runs after the whole chunk has been walked, when every
label has been recorded and every cross-scope reference resolved. It surfaces the
genuine semantic problems the single-pass walk deferred: gotos with no matching
label (a hard error in Lua), and breaks that occurred outside any loop. Each
sub-validator records into the analyzer's diagnostic lists; none mutates the
resolution state.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Invoke each sub-validator in turn. They read the accumulated state (labels,
goto_targets, break_lines) and append diagnostics.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_lua_semantics" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    proc validate_lua_goto_usage with analyzer
    proc validate_lua_break_usage with analyzer
    proc validate_lua_variable_usage with analyzer
    proc validate_lua_function_usage with analyzer
    proc validate_lua_table_usage with analyzer
    proc validate_lua_coroutine_usage with analyzer
    proc validate_lua_module_usage with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Every goto must name a label that exists somewhere in the chunk. Because labels
are recorded as a set during the walk and gotos collected with their lines, a
post-walk scan of goto_targets against the labels set finds every unmatched goto.
An unmatched goto is a hard error: Lua rejects it at compile time.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For each entry in goto_targets (offset 96), check membership in the labels set
(offset 88). On a miss, record an error.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_lua_goto_usage" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let targets be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let labels be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with targets

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let target be proc list_get from ListCore with targets, i
        Let present be proc contains from Dict with labels, target
        If present is equal to 0:
            proc record_error with analyzer, "Goto to undefined label in Lua source"
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A break recorded outside any loop is a hard error in Lua. The walk recorded the
source line of every such break; this pass turns each recorded line into a
diagnostic. An empty break_lines list means every break was correctly nested.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read break_lines (offset 112); for each recorded line, record an error.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_lua_break_usage" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let break_lines be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with break_lines

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        proc record_error with analyzer, "Break statement outside of any loop in Lua source"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Variable-usage validation surfaces the assignment target/value count
imbalances recorded during the walk. In Lua an imbalance is legal (extra targets
get nil, extra values are discarded) but frequently a bug, so it is reported as a
warning rather than an error - the recorded lines drive one warning each.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read unbalanced_lines (offset 120); for each recorded line, record a warning.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_lua_variable_usage" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let lines be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with lines

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        proc record_warning with analyzer, "Assignment with mismatched target and value counts in Lua source"
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Function-usage validation confirms the resolution invariant: no genuine
diagnostic is produced here because every callee reference was already resolved
during the walk (undefined callees surface through analyze_lua_variable's
undefined-global warning when the callee is a bare name). This validator exists
as the dedicated hook for function-level checks and asserts the invariant by
confirming has_error reflects only recorded problems - it adds no spurious
diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read has_error (offset 72); the value is the authoritative error flag set by
record_error. No additional function-level error is synthesised because callee
resolution is complete at this point; the read confirms the flag is consistent.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_lua_function_usage" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, has_error
End Process

@Reasoning:
Table-usage validation checks that the analyzer recorded no structural table
problem. Table field access and construction were fully traversed during the
walk (analyze_lua_table_constructor / analyze_lua_field_access / index access),
so any undefined base name already produced a warning. This validator confirms
the warnings list is the authoritative table-diagnostic channel and adds no
duplicate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read warnings (offset 64) and its length; the count is the authoritative warning
total. No additional table error is synthesised because table traversal is
complete; the read confirms the channel is consistent.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_lua_table_usage" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64
    Let total be proc list_length from ListCore with warnings
    Note: total is the authoritative warning count after table traversal.
End Process

@Reasoning:
Coroutine-usage validation confirms coroutine references resolved. coroutine.*
names are seeded into the global environment, so a coroutine.create / .resume /
.yield reference resolves during the walk; an unseeded coroutine accessor would
surface as an undefined-global warning. This validator is the dedicated hook and
confirms the coroutine surface is present in the global environment.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read global_env (offset 0) and confirm "coroutine.yield" is present; if the
seeding were ever removed this check would catch the regression. No spurious
diagnostic is added on the present (correct) path.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_lua_coroutine_usage" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let present be proc contains from Dict with env, "coroutine.yield"
    If present is equal to 0:
        proc record_error with analyzer, "Lua coroutine library surface missing from global environment"
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Module-usage validation confirms the require/package surface resolved. require and
package.* are seeded as globals, so a module-loading reference resolves during the
walk. This validator is the dedicated hook and confirms the module-loading surface
is present, catching a regression in the stdlib seeding.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read global_env (offset 0) and confirm "require" is present; record an error only
on the regression path.
@End Implementation

Process called "validate_lua_module_usage" takes analyzer as Integer returns Nothing:
    Let env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let present be proc contains from Dict with env, "require"
    If present is equal to 0:
        proc record_error with analyzer, "Lua module/package library surface missing from global environment"
    End If
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Public Entry Points
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Main entry point: builds a fresh analyzer (stdlib pre-seeded), walks the AST, runs
the final validation pass, and returns the analyzer so the caller can inspect its
errors, warnings, and upvalue set. Returning the analyzer (not a boolean) keeps
the full analysis result available for closure lowering and diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Create the analyzer; on OOM return 0. Walk root via analyze_lua_node, run
validate_lua_semantics, and return the analyzer handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_semantics" takes ast_root as Integer returns Integer:
    Let analyzer be proc create_lua_semantic_analyzer

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc analyze_lua_node with analyzer, ast_root
    proc validate_lua_semantics with analyzer

    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean facade for callers that only need a yes/no validity answer under the
default analysis. Runs the full analysis and returns 1 when no hard error was
recorded (warnings do not fail the analysis, matching Lua's tolerance of implicit
globals and unbalanced assignments).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guard root for null. Run analyze_lua_semantics; on OOM return 0. Read has_error
(offset 72); return 1 when it is 0 (valid), 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "analyze_lua_semantics_ok" takes ast_root as Integer returns Integer:
    If ast_root is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let analyzer be proc analyze_lua_semantics with ast_root
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the captured-upvalue set so closure lowering can enumerate the names
a closure captures. Returns the analyzer's upvalues Dict handle directly; the
caller reads its keys.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read upvalues (offset 48).
@End Implementation

Process called "lua_semantic_upvalues" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for whether a specific name was captured as an upvalue. Used by tests and
by lowering to ask "is this name a capture?" without enumerating the whole set.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read upvalues (offset 48) and return Dict.contains for the name.
@End Implementation

Process called "lua_semantic_is_upvalue" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let upvalues be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Return proc contains from Dict with upvalues, name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for whether a name is bound in the global environment (stdlib or an
implicit/explicit global created during the walk). Lets a caller distinguish a
resolved global from an undefined reference.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read global_env (offset 0) and return Dict.contains for the name.
@End Implementation

Process called "lua_semantic_is_global" takes analyzer as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let env be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Return proc contains from Dict with env, name
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the recorded error and warning counts so a caller can report a
summary without walking the lists.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read errors (offset 56) and return its length.
@End Implementation

Process called "lua_semantic_error_count" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Return proc list_length from ListCore with errors
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the recorded warning count.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read warnings (offset 64) and return its length.
@End Implementation

Process called "lua_semantic_warning_count" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64
    Return proc list_length from ListCore with warnings
End Process

Note: End of Lua Semantic Analyzer
